2:47pm on a Tuesday, I opened package.json to add one dependency and stopped counting at six TanStack packages already sitting there. Query, Router, Table, Form, plus two utility packages I didn’t remember installing. Nobody had scheduled a meeting about this. No RFC, no architecture doc, no line item in a sprint plan that said “adopt TanStack as our stack.”
It just happened, one PR at a time, over about four months. Cache invalidation got annoying, so Query went in. The App Router’s file conventions got in the way of a weird nested layout, so a few routes quietly moved to TanStack Router. Then Table showed up because the ops dashboard needed sorting and virtualization that the homegrown solution never quite nailed. By the time anyone stepped back to look at the dependency list, this was basically a second framework running inside the framework, and it worked better than the thing it replaced.
That’s the story with TanStack right now. It’s not a library anymore. It’s a slow, deliberate land grab on the parts of React that used to require either rolling your own or signing up for a framework’s opinions wholesale.
The query part everyone already knows
If you’ve touched a React app in the last few years you’ve probably used TanStack Query (still mentally filed under its old name, react-query, by half the industry). The pitch hasn’t changed: server state is not the same shape of problem as client state, stop shoving fetch results into Redux, let a cache do the deduping and refetching for you.
function useOrders(customerId: string) {
return useQuery({
queryKey: ["orders", customerId],
queryFn: () => fetchOrders(customerId),
staleTime: 60_000,
});
}function OrdersPanel({ customerId }: { customerId: string }) {
const { data, isPending, error } = useOrders(customerId); if (isPending) return <Skeleton />;
if (error) return <ErrorState error={error} />; return <OrderList orders={data} />;
}Nothing exotic here. What’s changed is how this fits with server components. A lot of teams assumed RSC made Query obsolete, since the server can just fetch and hand you data directly. In practice most of us still want client-side refetching, optimistic updates, and background revalidation for anything that changes after the initial render (carts, notifications, live dashboards). So the pattern that’s actually shipping in 2026 is server components for the first paint, Query hydrated on top for everything after. Not either/or. Both, awkwardly stapled together, working fine.
Router and start, the part that raises eyebrows
TanStack Router is where people start feeling defensive, because using it in a Next.js app kind of implies you don’t fully trust the App Router. Which, fair, a lot of us don’t. The App Router’s file-based conventions are powerful but they hide a genuinely large amount of behavior behind folder names and special files, and debugging a wrong render because you named a file loading.tsx instead of Loading.tsx in the wrong directory gets old.
TanStack Router leans the other way: routes are defined in code, fully typed, and the type safety extends all the way to your search params.
const routeTree = rootRoute.addChildren([
ordersRoute.addChildren([orderDetailRoute]),
]);const orderDetailRoute = createRoute({
getParentRoute: () => ordersRoute,
path: "$orderId",
validateSearch: (search) => ({
tab: search.tab === "returns" ? "returns" : "details",
}),
loader: ({ params }) => fetchOrder(params.orderId),
});That validateSearch bit is the sell. Your search params are typed and validated at the route level, not sprinkled through useSearchParams() calls with optional chaining everywhere. TanStack Start is the full-stack wrapper around this, giving you SSR and server functions without the App Router's specific set of conventions. It's not obviously better. It's a different set of tradeoffs, and if you already know the App Router cold, Start is more churn than it's worth. But for greenfield projects, or teams that got burned by App Router migrations, it's a real option now, not a science project.
The one people are actually talking about: TanStack DB
This is the part that made me sit up. TanStack DB is a sync layer that sits on top of Query and gives you local collections you can query reactively, with optimistic mutations that reconcile against the server.
const ordersCollection = createCollection(
queryCollectionOptions({
queryKey: ["orders"],
queryFn: fetchOrders,
getKey: (order) => order.id,
onUpdate: async (order) => {
await api.orders.update(order.id, order);
},
}),
);function useOverdueOrders() {
return useLiveQuery((q) =>
q.from({ order: ordersCollection })
.where(({ order }) => order.dueDate < Date.now())
.orderBy(({ order }) => order.dueDate),
);
}That’s a live, reactive, SQL-ish query over client-side data, with the sync and optimistic update handling done for you. This is squarely aimed at the local-first crowd, the people who’ve been eyeing Replicache or RxDB or Zero and wondering if they had to leave the React ecosystem to get that experience. Turns out, maybe not.
Is it fully baked? No. The docs still have gaps, the community examples are thinner than Query’s, and I would not put it in front of a Series A’s core billing flow yet. But the shape of it is right, and it’s the first time “local-first” hasn’t felt like a separate universe from “normal React app.”
The table piece nobody credits
Table is the least glamorous member of the family and probably the one paying the bills most directly. Our ops dashboard needed sortable, filterable, virtualized rows for a table that can run past 50,000 records on a bad day, and the homegrown solution we had before (a useMemo sorting a plain array, rendered with .map) started dropping frames the moment someone scrolled fast.
const table = useReactTable({
data: orders,
columns,
getCoreRowModel: getCoreRowModel(),
getSortedRowModel: getSortedRowModel(),
getFilteredRowModel: getFilteredRowModel(),
state: { sorting, columnFilters },
onSortingChange: setSorting,
onColumnFiltersChange: setColumnFilters,
});The headless part matters more than it sounds. TanStack Table gives you row models, sorting logic, and filter state, with zero opinions about what your table looks like. You bring your own markup or your own div grid, whatever your design system demands. That meant we matched the existing UI kit exactly instead of fighting a component library’s baked-in styles. Not flashy, but it’s the piece that quietly stopped breaking.
The migration cost people don’t mention in the threads
None of this is free, and the online discourse tends to skip the part where adopting even one TanStack library means someone on your team has to actually learn its mental model. Query’s cache invalidation rules are not intuitive on day one. Query keys have to be structured carefully or you end up with stale data bugs that are genuinely hard to trace, because the bug isn’t a crash, it’s a screen quietly showing last week’s numbers.
Two days got lost early on to a query key mismatch: one mutation used ["order", id], a related query used ["orders", id], and the invalidation never touched the query that needed refreshing. No error, just a support ticket three days later about a wrong order status. That's the tax nobody puts in the "why TanStack is great" blog post. The tools are good. The learning curve is real, and it's paid in incidents before it's paid in velocity gains.
So is this a framework now
Kind of? TanStack has never announced itself as a competitor to Next.js or Remix, and the individual pieces are explicitly designed to be adoptable one at a time, which is exactly how we ended up with it in our repo without a team decision. Nobody chose TanStack as a strategy. We chose Query for caching, then Router for one annoying nested layout, then DB for a feature that needed offline support. Each choice was small and locally reasonable. The sum of them is a stack.
The actual argument for TanStack, the one that keeps showing up in threads and blog posts, is that it doesn’t hide complexity, it exposes it and lets you deal with it in code instead of convention. Whether that’s a feature or a burden depends entirely on your team. If you like Next.js’s opinions, this will feel like more work for the same outcome. If you’ve ever spent an afternoon debugging why a layout re-rendered because of a file naming quirk, you’ll probably like having it all spelled out.
The routing hasn’t migrated wholesale. Table and Query are permanent at this point. Router is still confined to that one weird nested section nobody wants to touch. DB is in a spike branch that may or may not survive contact with the next sprint planning meeting. Nobody has a straight answer for when this became a TanStack shop, and honestly, that includes me.
